Ms Bishop said that she could find no good purpose that could be served by the execution of the two Australians, especially considering the strides they had made to improving the lives of fellow prisoners.  

She pointed to the work the pair had been involved in, including the education and encouragement they provided to others in the jail. 

'They are involved in the rehabilitation of other prisoners. Andrew Chan is now a Pastor. He has got a theology degree. He is providing a spiritual nourishment to other prisoners,' Ms Bishop said.

'Myuran Sukumaran is now an accomplished artist and he is taking art classes, master classes in art, and I just think that it would be a terrible injustice if these men were to pay for their crimes with their lives.'

Ms Bishop echoed Sukumaran's sentiments in his interview, agreeing that the men should not be put to death for their role in the drug smuggling ring.

'Yes, they are paying for their crimes, they are repaying their debt to society, but they shouldn't have to pay with their lives.' 

